  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Increasing Access to Healthcare in the Kambia District</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The health system in Sierra Leone is still recovering from the effects of the civil war.  Free health care for pregnant women and children under five years was introduced in 2010.  However the community-based strategy for maternal and child health is not being implemented.  Maternal and child mortality rates are still above the 2015 MDG target, and Kambia district indicators are significantly higher than the national average. 
This project will pilot a Community Health Education project in three communities in Kambia district. The project will test the assumption that community health workers can improve the links between public health facilities and remote communities and thereby contribute to reducing the high rates of maternal and child illness and death in Kambia district. Communities will know more about basic health messages, and the importance of timely health care.  The project will increase the number of pregnant women and children accessing free primary health care services.  Local communities will hold their health facilities to account through a range of health user groups and ante-natal groups.</narrative>
  </description>
